When Bunmi Olaoye (founder of Gangwolf360 and artmonnk) started a hastag on Twitter, WeAreNigerianCreatives, people around the world were clearly not ready for the outcome of the campaign. Since the start of the hashtag in July 2018, it has become evident that Nigerian artists can no longer be ignored.
Below are some of Nigeria’s best hyperrealist artists: <img class="aligncenter wp-image-878963 size-full lazyload" src="https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Kelvin-Okafor.-Photo-Kelvin-Okafor-Instagram.jpeg" alt="" width="1080" height="1340" srcset="https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Kelvin-Okafor.-Photo-Kelvin-Okafor-Instagram.jpeg 1080w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Kelvin-Okafor.-Photo-Kelvin-Okafor-Instagram-482x598.jpeg 482w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Kelvin-Okafor.-Photo-Kelvin-Okafor-Instagram-928x1152.jpeg 928w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Kelvin-Okafor.-Photo-Kelvin-Okafor-Instagram-449x557.jpeg 449w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Kelvin-Okafor.-Photo-Kelvin-Okafor-Instagram-898x1114.jpeg 898w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Kelvin-Okafor.-Photo-Kelvin-Okafor-Instagram-193x240.jpeg 193w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Kelvin-Okafor.-Photo-Kelvin-Okafor-Instagram-387x480.jpeg 387w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Kelvin-Okafor.-Photo-Kelvin-Okafor-Instagram-484x600.jpeg 484w" sizes="(max-width: 1080px) 100vw, 1080px" /> One of the most recognised hyperrealists in the International community, Okafor is famous for his drawings of Naomi Campbell, Beyonce, Rihanna and Nelson Mandela. Some of the celebrities he has drawn have expressed their joy publicly for been chosen as a muse. Processed with VSCO with preset A one-time Guardian Life spotlight subject, he is a self-taught 3-Dimensional artist who uses acrylic and oil to create astonishing images. His ability to convey more than two images in his unique social activism pieces has continued to leave art lovers in wonder. To read more about him and see his pictures, visit here. <img class="aligncenter wp-image-721399 lazyload" src="https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/Kareem-Waris.-Photo-AyoWole-Academy-of-Arts-e1534752903619.jpg" alt="" width="1280" height="719" srcset="https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/Kareem-Waris.-Photo-AyoWole-Academy-of-Arts-e1534752903619.jpg 801w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/Kareem-Waris.-Photo-AyoWole-Academy-of-Arts-e1534752903619-640x360.jpg 640w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/Kareem-Waris.-Photo-AyoWole-Academy-of-Arts-e1534752903619-320x180.jpg 320w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/Kareem-Waris.-Photo-AyoWole-Academy-of-Arts-e1534752903619-281x158.jpg 281w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/Kareem-Waris.-Photo-AyoWole-Academy-of-Arts-e1534752903619-562x316.jpg 562w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/Kareem-Waris.-Photo-AyoWole-Academy-of-Arts-e1534752903619-531x299.jpg 531w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/Kareem-Waris.-Photo-AyoWole-Academy-of-Arts-e1534752903619-1062x598.jpg 1062w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/Kareem-Waris.-Photo-AyoWole-Academy-of-Arts-e1534752903619-487x274.jpg 487w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/Kareem-Waris.-Photo-AyoWole-Academy-of-Arts-e1534752903619-600x337.jpg 600w" sizes="(max-width: 1280px) 100vw, 1280px" /> The world’s youngest hyperrealist is 11-year-old Kareem. Also, a Guardian Life spotlight subject, he caught the attention of Emmanuel Macron, president of France and the attention of the world after he drew the president in less than 2 hours. <img class="aligncenter wp-image-878966 size-full lazyload" src="https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Arinze-Stanley-Egbengwus-painting-of-Buhari.jpg" alt="" width="1080" height="1080" srcset="https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Arinze-Stanley-Egbengwus-painting-of-Buhari.jpg 1080w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Arinze-Stanley-Egbengwus-painting-of-Buhari-598x598.jpg 598w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Arinze-Stanley-Egbengwus-painting-of-Buhari-100x100.jpg 100w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Arinze-Stanley-Egbengwus-painting-of-Buhari-200x200.jpg 200w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Arinze-Stanley-Egbengwus-painting-of-Buhari-487x487.jpg 487w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Arinze-Stanley-Egbengwus-painting-of-Buhari-974x974.jpg 974w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Arinze-Stanley-Egbengwus-painting-of-Buhari-240x240.jpg 240w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Arinze-Stanley-Egbengwus-painting-of-Buhari-480x480.jpg 480w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Arinze-Stanley-Egbengwus-painting-of-Buhari-600x600.jpg 600w" sizes="(max-width: 1080px) 100vw, 1080px" /> Arinze Stanley is best remembered for using simple monochrome pencils to draw a portrait of President Muhammadu Buhari. The graduate of agricultural engineering is also the winner of the “World’s Best Self Portrait” at the American Art Awards, an award which sees the 25 best galleries in the US vote on 50 different categories from fashion to portraiture.